# Why a New Course on AI?

## “Vacuum” between CS and AI Curriculum

![](images/vacuum1.png){fig-align="center" width="100%"}

## “Vacuum” between CS and AI Curriculum

![](images/vacuum2.png){fig-align="center" width="100%"}

## Embedding AI Models in Games

- Use cases
  - NPC (Non-Player Character) Dialog and Interaction
  - Image models for sprite and character transformation
  - Audio models for game narration and effects
- Why embedded vs. OpenAI or Gemini?
  - Low Latency, Zero API cost, Data privacy
  - High-quality open-source models
  - Hardware advancements (e.g., Apple MLX, Gaming Hardware)

# CS-394/594: “How Generative AI Works”

## Course Information

::: {.columns}
:::: {.column width="50%"}
- Junior/Senior (300-level) course
- Masters (500-level) option
- 3 credit, 15-week course
- Weeks 1-8
  - Lecture-based with weekly assignments; 40% of grade
- Weeks 9-15
  - Project-based; 60% of grade
::::
:::: {.column width="50%"}
![](images/catalog.png){fig-align="center" width="75%"}
::::
:::

## Syllabus {style="font-size: 0.8em"}

- Understand the working principles and history of LLMs
- Create and deploy API-based clients, accessing LLMs hosted by different vendors
- Create agents and tools based on the MCP (Model Context Protocol) specification
- Explore and use models for image and audio recognition and generation
- Run generative models on local, laptop-based hardware (using CPU, GPU, NPUs)
- Evaluate and test generative models using industry benchmarks
- Increase the accuracy of models through fine-tuning
- Understand ethical, IP, and safety aspects

